10880010@unknown@formal@none@1@S@<article>Text mining</article>@1@2@@oe@30-11-2008
10880020@unknown@formal@none@1@S@'''Text mining''', sometimes alternately referred to as ''text [[data mining]]'', refers generally to the process of deriving high quality [[information]] from text.@1@22@@oe@30-11-2008
10880030@unknown@formal@none@1@S@High quality information is typically derived through the dividing of patterns and trends through means such as [[pattern recognition|statistical pattern learning]].@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10880040@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Text mining usually involves the process of structuring the input text (usually parsing, along with the addition of some derived linguistic features and the removal of others, and subsequent insertion into a [[database]]), deriving patterns within the structured data, and finally evaluation and interpretation of the output.@1@47@@oe@30-11-2008
10880050@unknown@formal@none@1@S@'High quality' in text mining usually refers to some combination of [[relevance (information retrieval)|relevance]], [[Novelty (patent)|novelty]], and interestingness.@1@18@@oe@30-11-2008
10880060@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Typical text mining tasks include [[text categorization]], [[text clustering]], [[concept mining|concept/entity extraction]], production of granular taxonomies, [[sentiment analysis]], [[document summarization]], and entity relation modeling (''i.e.'', learning relations between [[Named entity recognition|named entities]]).@1@32@@oe@30-11-2008
10880070@unknown@formal@none@1@S@==History==@1@1@@oe@30-11-2008
10880080@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Labour-intensive manual text-mining approaches first surfaced in the mid-1980s, but technological advances have enabled the field to advance swiftly during the past decade.@1@23@@oe@30-11-2008
10880090@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Text mining is an [[interdisciplinary]] field which draws on [[information retrieval]], [[data mining]], [[machine learning]], [[statistics]], and [[computational linguistics]].@1@19@@oe@30-11-2008
10880100@unknown@formal@none@1@S@As most information (over 80%) is currently stored as text, text mining is believed to have a high commercial potential value.@1@21@@oe@30-11-2008
10880110@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Increasing interest is being paid to multilingual data mining: the ability to gain information across languages and cluster similar items from different linguistic sources according to their meaning.@1@28@@oe@30-11-2008
10880120@unknown@formal@none@1@S@== Sentiment analysis ==@1@4@@oe@30-11-2008
10880130@unknown@formal@none@1@S@[[Sentiment analysis]] may, for example, involve analysis of movie reviews for estimating how favorably a review is for a movie.@1@20@@oe@30-11-2008
10880140@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Such an analysis may require a labeled data set or labeling of the [[Affect_(psychology)|affectivity]] of words.@1@16@@oe@30-11-2008
10880150@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A resource for affectivity of words has been made for [[WordNet]].@1@11@@oe@30-11-2008
