10891390@unknown@formal@none@1@S@There is the option in prose sung texts, less so in verse, of adding or deleting a syllable here and there by subdividing or combining notes, respectively, but even with prose the process is almost like strict verse translation because of the need to stick as closely as possible to the original prosody of the sung melodic line.@1@58@@oe@30-11-2008
10891400@unknown@formal@none@1@S@Other considerations in writing a singing translation include repetition of words and phrases, the placement of rests and/or punctuation, the quality of vowels sung on high notes, and rhythmic features of the vocal line that may be more natural to the original language than to the target language.@1@48@@oe@30-11-2008
10891410@unknown@formal@none@1@S@A sung translation may be considerably or completely different from the original, thus resulting in a [[contrafactum]].@1@17@@oe@30-11-2008
